// TEST: exec_record_field_collection_concat
// EXPECT: output "3;a-b-c"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python, rust, go
//
// A record field typed `List[String]` flows its element type through the
// read-only `List` built-ins (`concat`, `join`, `count`) when accessed as
// `record.field.concat(...)` (Q-r2-codegen-residue, codegen item b). The Go
// concern: `b.items` must carry the field's declared `[]string` element type
// into the `concat` IIFE — emitting `[]interface{}` there made the
// `func(__r []string, __o []string) []string` closure reject its arguments
// (`[]string` is not assignable to a `[]interface{}` parameter in Go), and a
// later typed use (`join`, a typed `let`) failed `go build`.
//
// This fixture pins that the field's `[]string` element type is recovered:
// `b.items.concat(["c"])` is `[]string`, `.count()` is the length, and `.join`
// concatenates with a separator — proven by running the program, not just
// inspecting Go source. js/ts/python/rust type collections natively and were
// already green; this keeps Go pinned alongside them. Verified already-correct
// in the field-typed-collection lowering (PR #168 generic List[T]-over-user
// types); the fixture guards against regression.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

record Bag {
  items: List[String]
}

fn extend(b: Bag, x: String) -> List[String] {
  return b.items.concat([x])
}

fn main() -> Void {
  let b: Bag = Bag { items: ["a", "b"] }
  let more: List[String] = extend(b, "c")
  println("${more.count()};${more.join("-")}")
}
